{
  "doc_id": "5025",
  "text": "HLA-E has a structural and functional mouse homolog, Qa-1 (H2-T23) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , and both human and mouse molecules have been shown to play diverse roles in the immune system. Both HLA-E and Qa-1 can present peptide antigens from intracellular pathogens such as Epstein Barr virus, cytomegalovirus, and Salmonella typhimurium to CD8 + T cells, resulting in activation of CTL activity against infected cells [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [25] . HLA-E and Qa-1 also both predominantly bind endogenous peptides derived from the leader sequence of MHC Ia molecules [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . For Qa-1, this single nonameric peptide is called Qa-1 determinant modifier (Qdm). The Qa-1/Qdm or HLA-E/peptide complex serves as a ligand for CD94/NKG2 receptors, which are expressed mainly on NK cells and a subset of CD8 + T cells [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
